Copper(I) iodide can be found in three forms (Keen, 1995): \begin{itemize} \item $\alpha$-CuI is stable above $673\pm8$K, and is in the \href{current_web_home_dir/AB8_cF36_225_a_f-001}{$\delta$-Bi$_{2}$O$_{3}$ structure}, with the iodine atoms on the (2a) Wyckoff positions and the copper atoms occupying 1/8 of the (32f) positions. \item $\gamma$-CuI (marshite) is the ground state, stable below $643\pm2$K, and is also in the $\delta$-Bi$_{2}$O$_{3}$ structure. \item In the intermediate temperature range $\beta$-CuI is generally agreed to be trigonal or hexagonal, but the exact structure is under dispute: \begin{itemize} \item (Kurdyumova, 1961) placed it in \href{current_web_home_dir/AB_hP12_156_3a2bc_3a2bc-001}{trigonal space group $P3m1$ \#156}.  Their unit cell is three times larger than the standard cell for this structure, and is now considered erroneous. (Abrahams, 2008). \item (B\"{u}hrer, 1977) placed it in \href{current_web_home_dir/A2B_hP6_187_gi_ad-001}{hexagonal space group $P\overline{6}m2$ \#187}, with the copper atoms partially occupying two sites. \item (Sakuma, 1988) placed it in \href{current_web_home_dir/AB_hP4_156_ab_ab-001}{trigonal space group $P3m1$ \#156} with a smaller unit cell than (Kurdyumova, 1961) and no disorder on the copper sites. \item (Keen, 1994) placed it in \href{current_web_home_dir/A2B_hP6_164_2d_d-001}{trigonal space group $P\overline{3}m1$ \#164} (this structure), with a unit cell similar to (B\"{u}hrer, 1977) and (Sakuma, 1988).  Like the former paper, the oxygen positions are disordered. \end{itemize} \end{itemize} ~ \vspace{-.25in} 
 The data from (Keen, 1994) was taken at 655K.  
 The copper sites are only partially occupied:  Cu-I (2d) is 85.1\% filled, with the remaining 14.9\% of the copper atoms going on the Cu-II (2d) site.
